## <span style="color:#00b4d8">🔷 Step 1: Find the Thevenin Equivalent Circuit at the Base</span>

To simplify the voltage divider circuit, we calculate the **Thevenin voltage (𝑉𝑇𝐻V TH​)** and **Thevenin resistance (𝑅𝐵R B​)**.

---

### <span style="color:#f4a261">Thevenin Voltage (𝑉𝑇𝐻V TH​):</span>

$$V_{TH} = V_{CC} \times \left(\frac{R_2}{R_1 + R_2}\right)$$

𝑉𝑇𝐻 = 𝑉𝐶𝐶 × (𝑅2 / 𝑅1 + 𝑅2)

$$V_{TH} = 22.5 \times \left(\frac{10}{90+10}\right) = 22.5 \times \left(\frac{10}{100}\right)$$

𝑉𝑇𝐻 = 22.5 × (10 / 90+10) = 22.5 × (10 / 100)

> [!success] Result $$\boxed{V_{TH} = 2.25 \text{ V}}$$ 𝑉𝑇𝐻 = ==2.25 V==

---

### <span style="color:#f4a261">Thevenin Resistance (𝑅𝐵R B​):</span>

$$R_B = R_1 | R_2 = \frac{R_1 \times R_2}{R_1 + R_2}$$

𝑅𝐵 = 𝑅1 ∥ 𝑅2 = 𝑅1 × 𝑅2 / 𝑅1 + 𝑅2

$$R_B = \frac{90 \times 10}{90+10} = \frac{900}{100}$$

𝑅𝐵 = 90 × 10 / 90+10 = 900 / 100

> [!success] Result $$\boxed{R_B = 9 \text{ k}\Omega}$$ 𝑅𝐵 = ==9 kΩ==

---

## <span style="color:#00b4d8">🔷 Step 2: Determine the Operating Point (Q-Point)</span>

The **Operating Point** consists of the **Collector Current (𝐼𝐶I C​)** and **Collector-Emitter Voltage (𝑉𝐶𝐸V CE​)**.

---

### <span style="color:#f4a261">A) Finding Collector Current (𝐼𝐶I C​):</span>

Apply **Kirchhoff's Voltage Law (KVL)** to the Base-Emitter loop:

$$V_{TH} - I_B R_B - V_{BE} - I_E R_E = 0$$

𝑉𝑇𝐻 − 𝐼𝐵𝑅𝐵 − 𝑉𝐵𝐸 − 𝐼𝐸𝑅𝐸 = 0

We know that $I_E = (1+\beta)I_B$. Substitute this into the equation:

𝐼𝐸 = (1+𝛽)𝐼𝐵. Substitute this into the equation:

$$V_{TH} - I_B R_B - V_{BE} - (1+\beta)I_B R_E = 0$$

𝑉𝑇𝐻 − 𝐼𝐵𝑅𝐵 − 𝑉𝐵𝐸 − (1+𝛽)𝐼𝐵𝑅𝐸 = 0

$$2.25 - I_B(9) - 0.6 - (1+55)I_B(1) = 0$$

2.25 − 𝐼𝐵(9) − 0.6 − (1+55)𝐼𝐵(1) = 0

$$1.65 - 9I_B - 56I_B = 0$$

1.65 − 9𝐼𝐵 − 56𝐼𝐵 = 0

$$1.65 = 65I_B$$

1.65 = 65𝐼𝐵

$$I_B = \frac{1.65}{65} = 0.02538 \text{ mA}$$

𝐼𝐵 = 1.65 / 65 = ==0.02538 mA==

Now, calculate 𝐼𝐶I C​:

$$I_C = \beta \times I_B = 55 \times 0.02538 \text{ mA}$$

𝐼𝐶 = 𝛽 × 𝐼𝐵 = 55 × 0.02538 mA

> [!success] Result $$\boxed{I_C = 1.396 \text{ mA}}$$ 𝐼𝐶 = ==1.396 mA== (approx. ==1.4 mA==)

---

### <span style="color:#f4a261">B) Finding Collector-Emitter Voltage (𝑉𝐶𝐸V CE​):</span>

First, find 𝐼𝐸I E​:

$$I_E = I_B + I_C = 0.02538 + 1.396 = 1.421 \text{ mA}$$

𝐼𝐸 = 𝐼𝐵 + 𝐼𝐶 = 0.02538 + 1.396 = ==1.421 mA==

Apply **KVL** to the Collector-Emitter loop:

$$V_{CC} - I_C R_C - V_{CE} - I_E R_E = 0$$

𝑉𝐶𝐶 − 𝐼𝐶𝑅𝐶 − 𝑉𝐶𝐸 − 𝐼𝐸𝑅𝐸 = 0

$$V_{CE} = V_{CC} - I_C R_C - I_E R_E$$

𝑉𝐶𝐸 = 𝑉𝐶𝐶 − 𝐼𝐶𝑅𝐶 − 𝐼𝐸𝑅𝐸

$$V_{CE} = 22.5 - (1.396 \times 5.6) - (1.421 \times 1)$$

𝑉𝐶𝐸 = 22.5 − (1.396 × 5.6) − (1.421 × 1)

$$V_{CE} = 22.5 - 7.818 - 1.421$$

𝑉𝐶𝐸 = 22.5 − 7.818 − 1.421

> [!success] Result $$\boxed{V_{CE} = 13.26 \text{ V}}$$ 𝑉𝐶𝐸 = ==13.26 V==

> [!tip] Verification (Because 𝑉𝐶𝐸V CE​ is **positive** and **less than** 𝑉𝐶𝐶V CC​, the transistor is safely operating in the ==Active Region==).

---

## <span style="color:#00b4d8">🔷 Step 3: Determine the Stability Factor (S)</span>

The formula for the **stability factor** in a voltage divider (self-bias) circuit is:

$$S = (1+\beta)\left[\frac{1 + \frac{R_B}{R_E}}{1 + \beta + \frac{R_B}{R_E}}\right]$$

𝑆 = (1+𝛽) [ 1 + 𝑅𝐵/𝑅𝐸 / 1 + 𝛽 + 𝑅𝐵/𝑅𝐸 ]

Substitute the known values (𝑅𝐵 = 9 kΩ, 𝑅𝐸 = 1 kΩ, 𝛽 = 55):

$$S = (1+55)\left[\frac{1 + \frac{9}{1}}{1 + 55 + \frac{9}{1}}\right]$$

𝑆 = (1+55) [ 1 + 9/1 / 1 + 55 + 9/1 ]

$$S = 56 \times \left[\frac{1+9}{56+9}\right]$$

𝑆 = 56 × [ 1+9 / 56+9 ]

$$S = 56 \times \left[\frac{10}{65}\right]$$

𝑆 = 56 × [ 10 / 65 ]

$$S = \frac{560}{65}$$

𝑆 = 560 / 65

> [!success] Result $$\boxed{S = 8.61}$$ 𝑆 = ==8.61==

---

