# <mark style="background:#FFB86CA6;">❓ Find the difference between IC − IREF assuming that all the transistors are identical. (Current mirror biasing)</mark>

---

## <span style="color:#00b4d8">📖 1. Introduction / Definition</span>

> [!info] Definition
> A **Current Mirror** is a circuit designed to copy a current through one active device (like a transistor) by controlling the current in another active device of a circuit, keeping the ==output current constant regardless of loading==. In Integrated Circuits (ICs), it is heavily used to provide constant bias currents ($I_C$) by mirroring a reference current ($I_{REF}$).

---

## <span style="color:#00b4d8">🔑 2. Circuit Description & Assumptions</span>

<img src="https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260306123434823070/1.webp" width="300" height="200" alt="Alt Text">

> [!important] Overview
> A basic BJT current mirror consists of two transistors, $Q_1$ and $Q_2$.
>
> $Q_1$ is connected as a **diode** (its Base and Collector are shorted together).
>
> The bases of $Q_1$ and $Q_2$ are ==tied together==, and their emitters are **grounded**.

> [!note] Assumptions for the derivation
> Both transistors are fabricated on the **same silicon chip**, meaning they are ==identical==. Therefore, they have the exact same current gain ($\beta$), base-emitter voltage ($V_{BE}$), and reverse saturation current.

---

## <span style="color:#00b4d8">📐 3. Mathematical Derivation (Step-by-Step)</span>

---

### <span style="color:#f4a261">Step 1: Relate the Base and Collector Currents</span>

Since $Q_1$ and $Q_2$ are identical and have their bases and emitters connected in parallel:

$$V_{BE1} = V_{BE2}$$

Because their base-emitter voltages are equal, their base currents and collector currents must also be equal:

$$I_{B1} = I_{B2} = I_B$$

$$I_{C1} = I_{C2} = I_C$$

---

### <span style="color:#f4a261">Step 2: Apply KCL at the Collector node of $Q_1$</span>

The reference current ($I_{REF}$) splits into the collector of $Q_1$ and the two base branches:

$$I_{REF} = I_{C1} + I_{B1} + I_{B2}$$

Substitute $I_{B1} = I_B$, $I_{B2} = I_B$, and $I_{C1} = I_C$ into the equation:

$$I_{REF} = I_C + I_B + I_B$$

$$I_{REF} = I_C + 2I_B$$

---

### <span style="color:#f4a261">Step 3: Introduce Current Gain ($\beta$)</span>

We know the standard BJT relationship between collector current and base current is $I_B = \frac{I_C}{\beta}$. Substituting this into the equation gives:

$$I_{REF} = I_C + 2\left(\frac{I_C}{\beta}\right)$$

$$I_{REF} = I_C \left(1 + \frac{2}{\beta}\right)$$

---

### <span style="color:#f4a261">Step 4: Find the Difference ($I_C - I_{REF}$)</span>

The question specifically asks for the difference between $I_C$ and $I_{REF}$. Rearranging our equation from Step 2:

$$I_C - I_{REF} = I_C - (I_C + 2I_B)$$

$$I_C - I_{REF} = -2I_B$$

Or, substituting $I_B = \frac{I_C}{\beta}$:

$$I_C - I_{REF} = -\frac{2I_C}{\beta}$$

> [!tip] Note
> The negative sign simply indicates that the output collector current $I_C$ is ==slightly less== than the reference current $I_{REF}$ by an amount equal to the current required to drive the two bases. The magnitude of this difference is $\frac{2I_C}{\beta}$.

---

## <span style="color:#00b4d8">⚖️ 4. Advantages & Disadvantages</span>

> [!success] Advantages
> - Eliminates the need for bulky biasing resistors, saving space on ICs.
> - Provides ==excellent thermal stability== because temperature variations in $Q_1$ exactly match those in $Q_2$, keeping the mirror effect stable.

> [!danger] Disadvantages
> - The output current $I_C$ is **not exactly equal** to $I_{REF}$ due to the base current losses (the $2I_B$ difference calculated above). Note: This is solved using advanced mirrors like the Widlar or Wilson current mirrors.

---

## <span style="color:#00b4d8">🔧 5. Applications</span>

> [!tip] Real-World Applications
> - **Operational Amplifiers (Op-Amps):** Used extensively as an active load and to provide constant tail current to differential amplifiers.
> - **Analog ICs:** Used in digital-to-analog converters (DACs) and timer ICs to provide stable reference currents.

---

## <span style="color:#ff6b6b">📦 6. Conclusion / Final Answer Box</span>

> [!abstract] For an examiner, highlight the final derived difference clearly:

>[!example]+ **Difference:**
> 
> $$\boxed{I_C - I_{REF} = -2I_B}$$
> 
> OR
> 
> $$\boxed{I_C - I_{REF} = -\frac{2I_C}{\beta}}$$

> [!tip] Summary
> (Assuming identical transistors, the output current $I_C$ is less than $I_{REF}$ by ==exactly twice the base current==).


