# <mark style="background:#FFB86CA6;">❓ Draw the circuit diagram of single stage BJT amplifier and explain the working. Also draw the frequency response.</mark>

---

## <span style="color:#00b4d8">📖 1. Introduction / Definition</span>

>[!info] Definition
> A **Single-Stage RC-Coupled BJT Amplifier** is a basic amplifying circuit that uses a single Bipolar Junction Transistor (BJT) to ==increase the strength of a weak AC input signal==. It employs a resistor-capacitor (RC) network for proper DC biasing and coupling the AC signal, making it one of the most widely used configurations for audio frequency amplification.

---

## <span style="color:#00b4d8">📝 2. Circuit Diagram Representation (How to draw it in the exam)</span>

<img src="https://www.eeeguide.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/Practical-Circuit-of-a-Transistor-Amplifier-in-CE-Configuration-with-Self-Biasing-01.jpg" width="300" height="200" alt="Alt Text">


>[!tip] Diagram Instructions
> Since I cannot draw directly, here is the exact layout you should sketch in your answer sheet, as explained by the professor in the video:
> 
> - **Transistor:** Draw an NPN BJT in a **Common Emitter (CE)** configuration (Emitter pointing downwards to ground).
> - **Biasing:** Draw a Voltage Divider Bias network using resistors $R_1$ and $R_2$ connected to the base terminal.
> - **Collector Resistor ($R_C$):** Connect $R_C$ between the Collector terminal and the positive power supply ($+V_{CC}$).
> - **Emitter Resistor & Capacitor:** Connect an Emitter Resistor ($R_E$) from the Emitter terminal to ground. In parallel with $R_E$, connect an Emitter Bypass Capacitor ($C_E$).
> - **Coupling Capacitors:** Connect an input coupling capacitor ($C_{in}$) in series with the AC input voltage ($V_{in}$) at the base. Connect an output coupling capacitor ($C_{out}$) from the collector terminal to the output ($V_o$).

---

## <span style="color:#00b4d8">⚙️ 3. Working Principle</span>

> [!important] Operation Phases
> **DC Biasing:** When no AC signal is applied, resistors $R_1, R_2, R_C,$ and $R_E$ set the exact operating point (Q-point) of the transistor in the ==center of the active region==.
> 
> **AC Operation:** 
> - When a weak AC input signal ($V_{in}$) is applied, it passes through $C_{in}$ and superimposes on the DC base bias voltage.
> - This causes the base current ($I_B$) to fluctuate according to the input signal.
> - Due to transistor action ($I_C = \beta I_B$), a small change in base current causes a **massive change** in the collector current ($I_C$).
> - The varying collector current creates a large varying voltage drop across $R_C$.
> - The output voltage ($V_o$), taken from the collector through $C_{out}$, is an ==amplified replica== of the input signal. In a CE configuration, the output signal is **180° out of phase** with the input signal.

---

## <span style="color:#00b4d8">📈 4. Frequency Response (Graph & Explanation)</span>

### <span style="color:#f4a261">How to draw the graph:</span>

> [!note] Graph Sketching Guide
> Draw an X-Y plane. The X-axis is Frequency ($f$) in Hz (usually on a logarithmic scale), and the Y-axis is Voltage Gain ($A_v$) in dB. The curve resembles a ==flattened bell shape==. Mark the maximum gain flat top as $A_{vmax}$. Mark the points on the curve where the gain drops to $0.707A_{vmax}$ (or -3dB). Drop dashed lines down to the X-axis from these points to label $F_L$ (Lower cut-off frequency) and $F_H$ (Upper cut-off frequency).

---

### <span style="color:#f4a261">Explanation of the 3 Regions:</span>

The gain of the amplifier is heavily dependent on the frequency due to capacitive reactance: 

$$X_C = \frac{1}{2\pi f C}$$

> [!danger] Low-Frequency Region ($f < F_L$)
> - At low frequencies, the capacitive reactance ($X_C$) of the coupling capacitors ($C_{in}, C_{out}$) and the bypass capacitor ($C_E$) is **very high**.
> - $C_{in}$ and $C_{out}$ drop a significant portion of the signal voltage.
> - $C_E$ fails to properly short circuit $R_E$, leading to negative feedback.
> - **Result:** Voltage gain sharply decreases.

> [!success] Mid-Frequency Region ($F_L < f < F_H$)
> - This is the ==useful operating range==.
> - The reactance of $C_{in}, C_{out},$ and $C_E$ becomes small enough to act as perfect short circuits for the AC signal.
> - Internal parasitic capacitances of the transistor act as open circuits.
> - **Result:** The voltage gain remains absolutely maximum and constant (flat region on the graph).

> [!warning] High-Frequency Region ($f > F_H$)
> - At very high frequencies, the internal junction capacitances of the BJT (Base-Emitter and Base-Collector depletion capacitance) show very low reactance.
> - They act as short circuits, essentially shunting (leaking) the AC signal to the ground.
> - Additionally, the transistor's current gain ($\beta$) naturally decreases at very high frequencies (emitter diode effect).
> - **Result:** Voltage gain drops off rapidly again.

> [!tip] Bandwidth
> (Note: The **Bandwidth (BW)** of the amplifier is defined as the useful mid-frequency range: 
> $$BW = F_H - F_L$$

---

## <span style="color:#00b4d8">⚖️ 5. Advantages & Disadvantages</span>

> [!success] Advantages
> - Excellent frequency response in the audio range (mid-frequency band is flat and wide).
> - Inexpensive and compact since it uses resistors and capacitors instead of bulky transformers.

> [!danger] Disadvantages
> - Poor voltage gain at very low frequencies (due to coupling capacitors).
> - It suffers from impedance matching issues (high output impedance, low input impedance) if connected to heavy loads directly.

---

## <span style="color:#00b4d8">🔧 6. Applications</span>

> [!tip] Real-World Applications
> - **Voltage Preamplifiers:** Used in the initial stages of public address systems (PA systems) to boost the weak signals from microphones.
> - **Audio Amplifiers:** Widely used in radios, tape recorders, and stereos.
> - **Signal Processing:** Used in instrumentation circuits where high-fidelity signal boosting is required before feeding the signal to ADCs (Analog-to-Digital Converters).

---

## <span style="color:#ff6b6b">📦 7. Conclusion</span>

> [!abstract] Summary
> The single-stage BJT amplifier is a fundamental building block in analog electronics, providing high, phase-inverted voltage gain that ==remains stable across the audio frequency spectrum== (Bandwidth) by carefully leveraging RC components.


