# <span style="color:#ffb703">🔶 Part (iii): Voltage to Current Converter of Grounded Load</span>

## <span style="color:#00b4d8">📖 1. Introduction / Definition</span>

> [!info] Definition
> A **Voltage-to-Current (V-I) Converter** is an Op-Amp circuit that produces an output current ($I_L$) directly proportional to the applied input voltage ($V_{in}$). In a "Grounded Load" configuration, one terminal of the load is ==connected to the ground==.

---

## <span style="color:#00b4d8">📝 2. Circuit Diagram Representation (How to draw in exam)</span>

> [!tip] Diagram Instructions
> - Draw an Op-Amp. Connect a resistor $R$ from the output to the inverting terminal ($-$). Connect another resistor $R$ from the inverting terminal to ground. (This makes it a non-inverting amplifier with a gain of 2).
> - Apply the input voltage ($V_{in}$) through a resistor $R$ to the non-inverting terminal ($+$).
> - Connect another resistor $R$ from the output to the non-inverting terminal ($+$).
> - Connect the Load Resistor ($R_L$) from the non-inverting terminal ($+$) directly to the **Ground**.

---

## <span style="color:#00b4d8">📐 3. Mathematical Derivation / Working</span>

> [!example] Derivation Steps
> Let the voltage at the non-inverting terminal be $V_1$ and the inverting terminal be $V_2$.
> 
> By **Virtual Short Concept**, $V_2 = V_1$.
> 
> Because the Op-Amp is in a non-inverting setup with equal feedback resistors ($R_f = R_1 = R$), the output voltage is:
> $$V_{out} = \left(1 + \frac{R}{R}\right)V_1 = 2V_1$$
> 
> Apply **KCL** at the non-inverting node ($V_1$):
> $$\text{Incoming Currents} = \text{Outgoing Current}$$
> $$I_1 + I_2 = I_L$$
> 
> $$\left[ \frac{V_{in} - V_1}{R} \right] + \left[ \frac{V_{out} - V_1}{R} \right] = I_L$$
> 
> Substitute $V_{out} = 2V_1$ into the equation:
> $$\frac{V_{in} - V_1 + 2V_1 - V_1}{R} = I_L$$
> 
> $$\frac{V_{in}}{R} = I_L$$

> [!abstract] Final Equation Box
> $$\boxed{I_L = \frac{V_{in}}{R}}$$

---

## <span style="color:#00b4d8">⚖️ 4. Advantages & Applications</span>

> [!success] Advantages
> The load current $I_L$ is ==entirely independent== of the load resistance $R_L$. It depends strictly on the input voltage and the precision resistor $R$.

> [!tip] Applications
> Used in LED and Zener diode testers, diode match finders, and industrial transmission lines (like 4-20mA current loops).



